  <discussion>Plants of Anoectangium aestivum often exhibit a comal tuft, and have leaves with multifid or occasionally 2-fid papillae, these dense and obscuring the cell lumens.  Specimens from Massachusetts identified as this species are Hymenostylium recurvirostrum.  Sporophytes are rare in the flora area.  Arizona specimens with blunt leaves have been named A. euchloron, representing a morphologically somewhat intergrading, wide-ranging tropical variant.</discussion>
